<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="377" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,332,575]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,368,395]" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Moths of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li et Wang" authorityYear="2002" box="[479,561,369,395]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Meleonoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="facialis">
<emphasis box="[479,561,369,395]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">facialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group share a yellow forewing with a dark costal spot and a dark apical patch (
<figureCitation box="[160,243,405,432]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1640,1665]" captionTargetBox="[193,1393,188,1575]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[183,1403,181,1584]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 6. Adults of Meleonoma spp. a. M. malacobyrsa (Meyrick, 1921) b. M. sp. (Mt. Longtang) c. M. sp. (Mt. Daming) d. M. sp. (Mt. Weibao) e. M. jigongshanica (Wang, 2003) f. M. paranthaedeaga (Wang, 2003) g. M. facialis Li et Wang, 2002 h. M. acutiuscula (Wang, 2004). Scale bars: 2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3758643" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3758643/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[211,243,405,432]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="6.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" unit="g" value="6.0">6g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
). In the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[504,586,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1826,1851]" captionTargetBox="[327,1285,187,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[243,1344,181,1800]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Male genitalia of Meleonoma spp. a. M. malacobyrsa (Meyrick, 1921), slide No. ZXJ19149 b. M. sp. (Mt. Longtang), slide No. ZXJ19136 c. M. sp. (Mt. Daming), slide No. ZXJ19134 d. M. sp. (Mt. Weibao), slide No. YAH15265 e. M. jigongshanica (Wang, 2003), slide No. L97210 f. M. paranthaedeaga (Wang, 2003), slide No. ZXJ19140 g. M. facialis Li et Wang, 2002, slide No. ZXJ19154 h. M. acutiuscula (Wang, 2004), slide No. ZXJ19170. Scale bars: 0.2 mm (b, g); 0.5 mm (a, c, d, e, f, h)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3758645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3758645/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[556,586,405,431]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="7.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" unit="g" value="7.0">7g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
), the uncus is sub-triangular, club-shaped, or long spine-shaped; the gnathos is absent or present; and the sacculus is separated from the valva, or only free distally. In the female genitalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1608,1633]" captionTargetBox="[201,1399,189,1553]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[188,1399,181,1583]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 8. Female genitalia of Meleonoma spp. a. M. malacobyrsa (Meyrick, 1921), slide No. LiSR15015 b. M. sp. (Mt. Longtang), slide No. ZXJ19163 c. M. sp. (Mt. Daming), slide No. YAH12313 d. M. sp. (Mt. Weibao), slide No. ZXJ19169 e. M. jigongshanica (Wang, 2003), slide No. ZXJ19161 f. M. paranthaedeaga (Wang, 2003), slide No. W98003 g. M. facialis Li et Wang, 2002, slide No. ZXJ19284 h. M. acutiuscula (Wang, 2004), slide No. ZXJ19167. Scale bars: 0.2 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3758647" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3758647/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="377">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[151,181,477,503]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="8.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="377" unit="g" value="8.0">8g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
), the antrum is heavily sclerotized in most species, the ductus bursae is sclerotized or membranous, and the corpus bursae lacks or has 1−2 signa.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
